<text>FORM AND FUNCTION
The ELISA test

If you get sick with a virus, clues to the nature of your illness can be found in your blood. You will likely have both antigens from the virus (parts of the virus) and antibodies created by your immune system to disable the virus by attaching to the antigen molecules that are part of the virus. The shape of the anitbodies is key to how they recognize specific antigens. Luckily a  technique -- called ELISA -- has been developed that can identify the presence of specific antibodies or antigens.


 

        
